ns instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnese Cornaro was born about 1180, in Venice, Veneto, Italy. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Michele Morosini dalla Sbarra."},"et":{"about 1180–":"umbes 1180–Surnud","1178–Male":"1178–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1203–1289":"1203–1289","1235–1300":"1235–1300","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1300":"1300","1289":"1289","1178":"1178","about 1202":"umbes 1202","Abt 1235":"umbes 1235","1180":"1180","Venice, Venezia, Veneto, Italy":"Venezia, Venezia, Veneto, Itaalia","Of, Venezia, Venezia, Italy":"Venezia, Venezia, Veneto, Itaalia","of Venezia, Italy":"Venezia, Veneto, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1180–":"noin 1180–Kuollut","1178–Male":"1178–Kuollut","1202–Male":"1202–Kuollut","1203–1289":"1203–1289","1235–1300":"1235–1300","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","about 1180":"noin 1180","1300":"1300","1289":"1289","1178":"1178","about 1202":"noin 1202","Abt 1235":"noin 1235","1180":"1180","Venice, Venezia, Veneto, Italy":"Venezia, Venezia, Veneto, Italia","Of, Venezia, Venezia, Italy":"Venezia, Venezia, Veneto, Italia","of Venezia, Italy":"Venezia, Veneto, Italia"},"fr":{"about 1180–":"environ 1180–Décédée","1178–Male":"1178–Décédé","1202–Male":"1202–Décédé","1203–1289":"1203–1289","1235–1300":"1235–1300","1180–Female":"1180–Décédée","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","about 1180":"environ 1180","1300":"1300","1289":"128